msgstr ""

#: ../../../userspace-api/media/v4l/subdev-formats.rst:149
msgid "Media Bus Pixel Codes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../userspace-api/media/v4l/subdev-formats.rst:151
msgid ""
"The media bus pixel codes describe image formats as flowing over physical "
"buses (both between separate physical components and inside SoC devices). "
"This should not be confused with the V4L2 pixel formats that describe, using "
"four character codes, image formats as stored in memory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../userspace-api/media/v4l/subdev-formats.rst:157
msgid ""
"While there is a relationship between image formats on buses and image "
"formats in memory (a raw Bayer image won't be magically converted to JPEG "
"just by storing it to memory), there is no one-to-one correspondence between "
"them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../userspace-api/media/v4l/subdev-formats.rst:162
msgid ""
"While the media bus pixel codes are named based on how pixels are "
"transmitted on parallel buses, serial buses do not define separate codes. By "
"convention, they use the codes that transfer a sample on a single clock "
"cycle, and whose bit orders from LSB to MSB correspond to the order in which "
"colour components are transmitted on the serial bus. For instance, the MIPI "
"CSI-2 24-bit RGB (RGB888) format uses the MEDIA_BUS_FMT_RGB888_1X24 media "
"bus code because CSI-2 transmits the blue colour component first, followed "
"by green and red, and MEDIA_BUS_FMT_RGB888_1X24 defines the first bit of "
"blue at bit 0. While used for 24-bit RGB data on parallel buses, the "
"MEDIA_BUS_FMT_RGB888_3X8 or MEDIA_BUS_FMT_BGR888_1X24 codes must not be used "
"for CSI-2."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../userspace-api/media/v4l/subdev-formats.rst:176
msgid "Packed RGB Formats"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../userspace-api/media/v4l/subdev-formats.rst:178
#: ../../../userspace-api/media/v4l/subdev-formats.rst:2766
msgid ""
"Those formats transfer pixel data as red, green and blue components. The "
"format code is made of the following information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../userspace-api/media/v4l/subdev-formats.rst:181
msgid ""
"The red, green and blue components order code, as encoded in a pixel sample. "
"Possible values are RGB and BGR."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../userspace-api/media/v4l/subdev-formats.rst:184
msgid ""
"The number of bits per component, for each component. The values can be "
"different for all components. Common values are 555 and 565."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../userspace-api/media/v4l/subdev-formats.rst:187
#: ../../../userspace-api/media/v4l/subdev-formats.rst:2780
msgid ""
"The number of bus samples per pixel. Pixels that are wider than the bus "
"width must be transferred in multiple samples. Common values are 1 and 2."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../userspace-api/media/v4l/subdev-formats.rst:191
#: ../../../userspace-api/media/v4l/subdev-formats.rst:2784
#: ../../../userspace-api/media/v4l/subdev-formats.rst:8678
#: ../../../userspace-api/media/v4l/subdev-formats.rst:8798
msgid "The bus width."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../userspace-api/media/v4l/subdev-formats.rst:193
msgid ""
"For formats where the total number of bits per pixel is smaller than the "
"number of bus samples per pixel times the bus width, a padding value stating "
"if the bytes are padded in their most high order bits (PADHI) or low order "
"bits (PADLO). A \"C\" prefix is used for component-wise padding in the most "
"high order bits (CPADHI) or low order bits (CPADLO) of each separate "
"component."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../userspace-api/media/v4l/subdev-formats.rst:200
#: ../../../userspace-api/media/v4l/subdev-formats.rst:2791
#: ../../../userspace-api/media/v4l/subdev-formats.rst:8685
msgid ""
"For formats where the number of bus samples per pixel is larger than 1, an "
"endianness value stating if the pixel is transferred MSB first (BE) or LSB "
"first (LE)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../userspace-api/media/v4l/subdev-formats.rst:204
msgid ""
"For instance, a format where pixels are encoded as 5-bits red, 5-bits green "
"and 5-bit blue values padded on the high bit, transferred as 2 8-bit samples "
"per pixel with the most significant bits (padding, red and half of the green "
"value) transferred first will be named ``MEDIA_BUS_FMT_RGB555_2X8_PADHI_BE``."
msgstr ""

